The "creators" distributed humanoids on different planets where there was a need to interfere in atmospheric conditions (in the case of people, biblical catastrophes, floods, etc.). The prometheus' humanoids developed the most and reached the creators, curious engineers destroyed their "Gods" and took over their name (does not it remind something?). If they saw competition in other "humanoids" - they destroyed them (they saw it in people), while the less developed ones that they saw in the gods left alive (engineers from covenat). Just history is coming round.
It's nice if Ridley used something, I hope that at least he can do one movie and close the buckle, these two films may gain on continuation. Then move the action 500 years into the future (in the end of the prequels leave an open gate - there are more spaces after the egg galaxy), completely "detach" from previous movies and just do a two-hour closed story, not some new trilogies, only different films, various director's visions, different interpretations with strangers in the background.
Recently there have been rumors about the show, or some short films there - this is a good track, there will be a lot of younger creators with their interesting ideas, but Scott must also finish what he started, you can not leave it.

Title: Alien: Covenant | Teaser Trailer [HD] | 20th Century FOX
Comment:
This is, basically, the sequel to Ridley Scott's prior film _Promethius_ and manages to finally answer such questions as who created the alien monsters in that and the earlier _Alien_ films, which are actually a highly advanced biological weapon capable of destroying all nonbotanical lifeforms on a planet,  and what happened to them.  This film, like _Promethius_, involves a declining humanity's attempt to find a new world to colonize while speculating about where humanity came from and what its destiny will be.  Much of the action is catalyzed by the sinister, human despising android "David" who reappears in this film and continues his efforts to assist in the demise of humanity.  Like the prior films, there is much darkness, dampness, and blood splattering attacks by the alien creatures.  This time, however, they even seem immune to bullets.  The space scenes look realistic and there is much action.  All of the standard plot elements are redone in this film and the overall plot is mildly interesting.  They even threw in a bit of surprise ending not seen before.  However, I found _Promethius_ to be a more interesting film because of its plot, but this one is an adequate sequel and worth viewing, imo. 

If one is new to these Ridley Scott films, he may be surprised at how different they appear from the usual _Star Trek_ films.  There is no Federation of Planets, no vast wars raging in space, no teleporters, and no phasor guns.  The spacecraft are hulking masses of metal propelled through space by glowing thrusters in their trailing ends and there is only some vague mentioning of making "jumps" through space.  Trips to distant star systems are not completed in days, but, rather, require years during which the astronauts, future colonists aboard the spaceship "Covenant" in this film, must sleep with greatly lowered metabolisms in special hibernation tubes.  By the standards of the ST films, the technological view of the future this film and its antecedents present is somewhat primitive.  I suspect the actual technology of the future will be somewhere between what is seen in ST movies and Scott's films.

Comment: Prometheus is my favourite film, to move on the original Alien movie in such a creatively original way is genius. The android David preaning himself to look and sound like his hero, the glorious Peter O'toole in David Leane's 7 Academy award winning movie Lawrence of Arabia, recounting the lines "....... the trick is not minding it hurts" is chilling when you think what follows and his disregard for human life. The production values are stratospheric, the quality shows in the cinematography, equipment, vehicles, aliens, sets, effects and cgi. The directing and acting are peerless. But for me it's that story revelation that humans are the product of Engineers, what an audacious and brilliantly original idea.

Origins - Darwinism and DNA

I recently watched a video in which Neil deGrasse Tyson talked about Darwin and DNA diversity. In the video Tyson stated that the human embryo has gills that develop into the inner ear later on in the development of the fetus.

Does all life have gills present in the embryonic stage? If not can the lineage of such animals that develop without gills be traced back to an area when evolutionary change would have determined that life no longer needed gills to breathe? Life that developed in space on the way to Earth could have developed gills inside of the shell to help assist in development. Life developing in this manner though would have taken a very long time to develop as its need to roam a planet had not yet been established. A stasis if you will. 

Also since all life is contained in a fluid in the womb then life would have arrived on Earth in a similar type of fluid to that of the embryonic sack. 

Since all animals need water, except for a few who live in acidic water, then life would have come to Earth encapsulated in shells of water with some sort of embryonic fluid protecting the developing life.The embryo would then have used the water shell as a source of nutrients that it would also use to gather microbial carbon dust bits as it traveled through space and eventually to Earth.

Since water has been determined to be older than the Earth and that life would not have survived the Earth during its very hot years of forming, a model of the Earth when it first began to too cool to the point of allowing frozen water to slowly melt would be a good start to determine when life was seeded on Earth. 

If life in the modern world that does not develop gills during the embryonic development phase but has so in its lineage during prehistoric times then we can trace the evolution of life on Earth to a point of origins in space as well possibly creating a link between all species that would communicate somehow that we were on Earth and no longer needed gills during the development stage. Gills that suggest that primordial life at one time was sentient in the womb and thought for itself and needed to breathe the womb fluid until the umbilical cord of the mother was later introduced when the first male and female species mated and had offspring.

Life on Earth would not have had the prerequisites for gills once the water melted on Earth containing the embryo's. Life that came to Earth must therefore have developed gills as a means of breathing while on the way to Earth. 

It would need to be determined at what rate ice would melt but not melt enough to expose the embryonic sack inside but allowed the embryo once on Earth to seed its DNA, for plants, in the ground and at what rate the ice would melt that would then allow the life inside to walk the Earth.

Comment:
Anyone know what year the movie is taking place in it would answer alot 
of questions riddling the comment box. Also the Neomorph coming from a 
spore instead of goo is an interesting concept, as aliens still have the
 beloved egg.  
Movies taking place in order of years to explain the concepts of the species evolutions below.
93 AD - Prometheus initial scene, where an Engineer sacrifices himself in a LV-223 waterfall.
1504 AD - Scene from Alien vs. Predator where Predators come in a right of passage in the Inca Civilization.
2004 AD - Happenings from Alien vs. Predator and Aliens vs. Predator: Requiem.
2064 AD - A Elizabeth Shaw memory from that time is shown in a memorial device system seen by David in Prometheus.
2089 AD - Elizabeth Shaw and Charles Holloway discover a star map in a Scottish cave, dating back to 35 000 years.
2093 AD - Major happenings in Prometheus expedition.
2094 AD - Catastrophic happenings that destroys Prometheus crew, except Shaw and David.
2124 AD - Happenings from Alien.
2179 AD - Ripley is rescued from the Outer Rim.
2181 AD - Ripley is taken to Gateway Station.
2183 AD - Major happenings from Aliens, in Hadley's Hope.
2184 AD - Happenings from Alien 3.
2386 AD - Ripley is resurrected.
2434 AD - Major happenings from Alien: Resurrection.So when does this movie take place and fall into this timeline does it fill in or does it expand?

Title: Alien: Covenant | Teaser Trailer [HD] | 20th Century FOX
Comment: It picks up after Prometheus. The actress that played Shaw was confirmed to have had some film time although we don't really know to what degree. The story starts with this ship of colonists picking up a distress signal (which I believe was probably activated by Shaw) on this planet so they stop to investigate. Don't forget, at the end of Prometheus they were en route for the Engineers homeworld so this is probably that world they were talking about therefor there probably will be more Engineer story development. Plus, this movie has the original android David in it along with the new one (I believe his name is Walter) so there is another link between Prometheus and Alien: Covenant. I have full faith that the Prometheus story we saw is going to be developped further in this movie but with aliens now in the picture. It`s confirmed that there are TWO different aliens in this movie. The classic Xenomorph, and the new Neomorphs. I speculate that the Neomorph is the one bursting out the back that infects through the ear. We`ll see somehow at some point how the Xenomorph gets introduced. I am personally VERY excited for this movie and can`t wait for May 19

Title: Alien: Covenant | Teaser Trailer [HD] | 20th Century FOX
Comment: It's amazing how fans are complaining AGAIN. The biggest criticism of Prometheus was the lack of xenomorphs. Aside from the confusing storylines, Prometheus was a good movie and an intro to the entire Xenomorph storyline. This IS the sequel to Prometheus and part of a prequel trilogy that will lead to the events of the original Alien movie. Once you understand this it all makes sense. Yes, the captain does stand curious as the egg opens up but SO DID CAIN in the original Alien. For the brief second between the egg opening and the launch of the facehugger there is no time for deliberation or "maybe this is dangerous", it all happens to fast. And for those complaining of the goofiness of the shower scene, the tail is meant as a sexual/phalic conotation AGAIN displayed in the original Alien with Lambert. We all complained that Prometheus wasn't a true prequal so Ridley redirected the story back to the events of Alien. Shouldn't we be salivating some Alien juice for this movie! It brings Alien back to legitimate, quality movie making - so that we can forget the horrendous Alien Resurrection comedy and those ahem Alien / Predator made for tv fluff movies. This is going to be an amazing return to Xeno land. It's the movie we've waited for.

Comment:
Hopefully it's still going to respect the old great aliens movies, at least 1 and 2, as canon still. 

To remove the second movie as such would be one of the greatest heresy moves in sci fi for all time. Unlike easily triggered folks this is not a claim of personal onion, but of fact. The second movie is one of the first of its kind and style to lay the foundations of corporate and military styles and ownershipclaims, and other benchmarks and material for decades and more decades to come. 

If you remove it from canon you WILL vaporize your credibility and no one will respect or care for the movies you make after. 

Throw risky curves, even off tech jumps for some ships like promethous, But remember where it all came from, where it's brand was made immortal. Never replace and undo it like so many other franchises. Always remember that second movie and always honor it's existence in the timeline. 

You've been warned. Do not undo this cash cow you have by trying to remove the wrong parts. It will make the Ghostbusters fallout look like a small disagreement. You will shatter your franchise upon the rocks of those who will never forgive, and rightfully so. 

Add on, do not take away. DO NOT retcon ALIENS. 


EVER!

Comment:
I was hoping Noomi Rapace's character Elizabeth Shaw would still be the main protagonist... like a continuation of her journey from each movie onward, much like Ellen Ripley was for the original trilogy. But from the looks of it, it doesn't appear to be so.

I'm kind of disappointed in that, as I was looking forward with anticipation the progression of her character into each new film, especially with the cliffhanger that 'Prometheus' ended with. Instead, seems like she is most likely killed off early in Covenant and a (mostly) new cast with a different protagonist will take over.

Kind of a bummer for me but I'm still looking forward to this film.

Title: Alien: Covenant | Teaser Trailer [HD] | 20th Century FOX
Comment:
So for everyone confused: 
This is a sequel to "Prometheus" which is part of a 3 part prequel to the first "Alien"
Michale Fassbender is playing two androids in this movie, David from the first one and Walter part of the new crew
This is the home planet of the engineers "paradise" 
Set 10 years after Prometheus
Shaw, the girl who was the last survivor of Prometheus is in this movie but only has a minor roll
There are xenomorphs and a neomorph 
The way the crew starts to get infected is:
via spores from this spheres that are on/near trees
They enter a cave where there is the black goo dripping from the stalactites 
Also a traditional face hugger
Moving along the new crew is part of the covenant ship, they were sent to the engineers planet to colonize it but they still don't know anything about what happened with the ship and crew of the Prometheus

Comment: Question. If this colony ship, the Covenant, is traveling to a very far off planet on the other side of the galaxy which has to be farther off than LV-223 in 'Prometheus' who's to say that this ship didn't set sail before the Prometheus? Other side of the galaxy (from the movie description) has to be a lot farther off than LV-223. Let's say it's 6 or 7 and maybe even 10 times farther off than LV-223. That could be at least 20 years travel which would place the ships departure ten years before the Prometheus. The events from Prometheus could have actually happened while the entire colony was in hibernation. Of course the fact that Weyland Yutani is now the company would dismiss all of this speculation. Just hoping they don't write themselves into a space travel conundrum.

Comment:
I have no problem with bringing back the aliens IF they were part of the story, rather than the focus of it. R. Scott said that Prometheus was supposed to be in the same universe as Alien, but have it's own story and direction and the same with it's sequels. He seems to have changed his mind and now it is back to the old aliens again. I really wanted to find out more about the engineers since they could create a whole host of new aliens. It would have been cool if they went in the direction of Avatar in the sense of a new world with it's own unique environment and fauna, with the Engineers being the dominant race with their technology.

I'm kinda disappointed. I would much rather see the giant tentacled monster again, and the giant worm things. New alien types rather than the old one.

Comment:
I  love the Alien franchise, but this just seems like a rehash of the same things we've seen...People stumble upon alien eggs, someone gets impregnated, chest bursts and alien pops out, corporation has a mole who needs to secure and Alien to study in order to weaponize. 

If they are going to make more of these then please give me Neil Bloomkamp's Alien 5 with Corporal Hicks, and Ripley. Might be more likely to shine more of a light on the military industrial complex in the alien universe. Maybe how they are in bed with Weyland Yutani or how they clash with the corporations

I'll still see this movie and probably think its fine, but not great. I have a feeling some of the characters will be really memorable (Danny McBride, the biggest reason I want to see this)

Comment: I don't know why, but something just seems a little "off" about what I'm seeing here. Maybe it's because it seems to be retreading the original Alien and Prometheus, or maybe it's because of the more overt, and seemingly less subtle horror, but something about what I'm seeing in this footage has me a little worried. When I see two people being slaughtered in a shower together, I think of some cheesy slasher flick like Friday the 13th or something. Alien doesn't exactly come to mind. I'm still going to watch it in theatres. I watched AvP-R of all things. But I can't help but be a little concerned and I just wish I knew why.

Comment: The flat ship is not the covenant. The plot summary tells us that Covenant is a colony ship. The trailer shows us three different ships. The first ship is the crashed engineer-designed horseshoe shaped ship which the covenant crew presumably comes across in the planet they are in. No problem about this one. The second ship is the one that is seen exploding in one of the scenes. In another scene, the crew steps out of this ship on to the planet along with the new Fassbender android. The third ship is the flat one seen early on in the trailer. The exploding shop is not obviously the falt ship. But if we assume that the exploding ship is a drop ship of the falt ship, then we need to explain the scene where the flat ship cruises over a lake. Whoever is riding the falt ship doesn't need a drop ship to get crew on the ground.

Title: Alien: Covenant | Teaser Trailer [HD] | 20th Century FOX
Comment:
I'm amazed at all of this griping about how there's no 'story' in this trailer.

God forbid a trailer not spell out a film and plot (which has become commonplace in Hollywood recently).

There have also been disagreements about how there should be a 'Giger' inspired landscape.  What's wrong with something new?  Ridley knows that his creation has been played out and wants to deliver something more intriguing and expand on the universe.

I think Fox (along with Ridley) listened when he saw how polarizing Prometheus was.  

Alien: Covenant is a sequel to Prometheus, but he's decided not to run a story that branches off on its own path in the same 'alienverse'.  He wants a direct lead in to the events of 'Alien'.  Answer the who and why.  I'm particularly interested in Weyland-Yutani's obsession with the xeno.

I'm pretty excited for this film...

Title: Alien: Covenant | Teaser Trailer [HD] | 20th Century FOX
Comment: I have a theory on how Prometheus and Alien: Covenant are tied together. The Alien franchise has a history of having the xenomorph sneak onto an escape ship without the crew/escapee knowing. At the end of Prometheus we see a new xenomorph being born from the engineer that was infected by the extremely large face hugger. What if that same xenomorph was able to unknowingly sneak into Shaw's ship when she escaped? It is entirely possible given the precedent set forth in prior films. I think it did, I think it also badly injured Shaw and impregnated her and she birthed either the first classic xenomorph from all the original films, or a queen xenomorph. I think this causes her ship to crash on the planet that Alien: Covenant takes place on. I also think that David, or David's head rather, whom she took with her was able to send out some kind of signal to the Weyland company alerting them to their location. The Weyland company sends out this crew to investigate what happened in the guise of an "expedition" to find a suitable planet for colonization. We see another functioning David android as part of the crew in the trailer, which leads me to believe this is the case. The crew is unknowingly lead right to this and then all hell breaks loose. That's what I'm thinking is the plot.

Title: Alien: Covenant | Teaser Trailer [HD] | 20th Century FOX
Comment:
I remember reading what was supposedly a leaked early script of Alien 3 in which the survivors of Aliens arrive on a space station and the alien turns out to be an infectious lifeform that mutates people into aliens. I remember thinking that was the biggest betrayal you could give to the franchise that gave us both one of the greatest horror films and one of the greatest action sci-fi's ever. Turning the xenomorph into John Carptenter's The Thing what the hell were they thinking?

Then I watched Prometheus and I went "Oh, they kept that idea. Jesus Christ, talk about having no idea what makes your franchise memorable." And now we have Alien Covenant which seems to have no only dropped the GOOD aspects of Prometheus but kept the awful ones and crammed it into a proper Alien film just in case anyone had some hope that the two would become separate concepts. You thought maybe the Alien as an icon of horror and science-fiction and indeed the film industry as a whole would somehow survive this desperate attempt to break and twist it into something utterly unrecognizable, but nope, here's Alien Covenant to really twist that last nail into the coffin and make the argument clear that for whatever reason Ridley Scott has developed a massive inferiority complex concerning John Carpenter's suspense masterpiece and is going to spend an entire trilogy of films mutilating the franchise he created into a pretentious Thing ripoff. 

Can't wait to see it. It's going to be a sublime train wreck. But at least we'll get Michael Fassbender as pouty Commander Data again and that'll be worth it, won't it?

Comment:
Guys, calm down! :) 
This trailer was great, because it didn't show much of the story, like 
all good trailers should! All we know so far is... there will be an 
Alien - which is awesome! ^^ - and there will be people who have to deal
 with it. 
HOWEVER, the story of Prometheus (very good one) will continue most 
likely. We'll  learn more about David, what happend to Shaw, probably 
more about the Engineers themselves, maybe their homeland and hopefully a
 bit more about their amazingly dangerous (but also very potent) 
substance - "the black goo". 

AND let's not forget! Ridley Scott said there will be 3 Sequels to 
Prometheus (which is basically "Alien 0") with the last of these 
sequels, Nr. 3, leading into the very first Alien movie. So it will be 
like: 

- Alien prequel movie 0 (known as Prometheus, introducing the alien 
universe: the Space Jockeys, Weyland Yutani Corp/Peter Weyland himself 
and his motivations, Androids, and certain incidents that "may" have 
lead to the creation of the "alien species") 
- Alien prequel movie 1 (>> which is Alien Covenant <<)
- Alien prequel movie 2 (>> title yet unknown <<)
- Alien prequel movie 3 (>> title yet unknown >> BUT, 
according to Scott THIS will be the movie that leads directly into first
 Alien from 1979). 

So, let's just wait and see what Alien Covenant is all about, before you
 all jump to conclusions AND don't forget, there will be 2 more movies 
coming and fleshing out the "prequel trilogy", BUT most importantly: 
let's be happy and thankfull that we all  get a new amazing Sci-Fi movie
 made by Ridley Scott himself! :)

Title: Alien: Covenant | Teaser Trailer [HD] | 20th Century FOX
Comment: I'm totally hyped !  When I saw  Alien in 1979, this film wrecked me, mentally & emotionally.  The thought of anything having to do with biology repulsed me for years.  It was weeks before I was able to eat normally again.  And even the slightest glimpse of the Alien trailer, after it was syndicated to television would put me into a traumatic depression for years to come.  A likening to what I felt has been captured in the SCORN trailer.  (Very GIGER).  In the original Alien, the atmosphere was like a dreamy nightmare.  It was cold, dirty, & gritty.  From the beginning, the crew were already on edge and the atmosphere was tense.  They were regular people with regular jobs.  They were of different ages - (unlike the "cool" 20 somethings you see in every movie today)  They resonated with me because those people were like my neighbors or my family - It added to the horror, the feeling  that no one could keep me safe.  It was pure dread - pure fear.  I hope that Covenant will scare me that bad again ! 💀

Comment: By the looks of the trailer, they are trying to recapture that suspenseful horror feeling of the 1st movie. If that is the case, then they are likely to fall into the trap of making it EXACTLY the same. The thing about horror is that if you KNOW what the monster is, how it thinks and where it came from, you lose interest and it stops scaring you. For this to be a legitimately good movie, there NEEDs to be some new elements in which the audience wont expect, otherwise it will be a cheap rehash.

Title: Alien: Covenant | Teaser Trailer [HD] | 20th Century FOX
Comment:
If you've been following the development of this film, it's very much a Prometheus sequel and will give us the answers that Prometheus didn't.

If you're not familiar with the behind the scenes stuff, then this trailer would be quite confusing, especially seeing Fassbender with a different crew - that's because it's not David, but another Android.  David is the man in the cloak shown later in the trailer and by the looks of things, he's been a very naughty robot.  There will be engineers and Shaw will return, but most likely in a small cameo.  The planet in this trailer is the Engineer's homeworld.

The Engineer ship discovered by the Covenant crew in the trailer is the same ship Shaw and David used to escape LV-223 at the end of Prometheus.  Obviously, something went wrong because there's an alien egg on the ship, and it looks as though David has coaxed one of the Covenant members to investigate it knowing what the outcome will be (David's in the background of that shot).

Overall, judging from what we know about the story and this trailer, this film will be very dark, much like the first film.

Title: Alien: Covenant | Teaser Trailer [HD] | 20th Century FOX
Comment:
Been excited about this movie. However, nothing in this trailer got me excited. Really, it just looked plain old average. Another new, boring, unprepared crew, who encounter an Alien. Look. You have rights to the single greatest fictional horror creature ever created yet the genius writers and producers at Hollywood can't seem to come up with an original movie. Maybe in thirty years we'll have some better Alien material. The franchise have been a jumbled joke since Alien 3. I don't think this movie will be bad, but I don't see it being great either. You can't re-do an "Alien" movie. It isn't the 1970's, the Alien creature is no longer a new, edgy concept anymore (nor surprising - we know they chest burst, we know what they are now), and the cinema viewer of 2016 is not as naive as the cinema viewer of 1979. You have to understand that fact and adapt. Hollywood never adapts, they just force-feed people the same rehash. They succeed in making money because there simply is no real alternative for the people. They monopolize the film industry. It's like fashion: you buy what is out there, and what is out there is what is "in".

And yes, I'm aware this is a Prometheus prequel of sorts, taking place pre-Alien, and not a straight Alien remake. But who are you kidding? Yourself?

Comment: I have mixed feelings about this. Firstly the premise looks very similar to Prometheus, scientists going to another planet clueless of what is there, being kinda careless about what they do, and then there are chase scenes and stuff. In Prometheus, it was the engineers and the primitive xenomorph, here it looks like the actual xenomorph, looks like its gonna be a similar progression in story like Prometheus, its cool they're making this whole prequel thing to the actual alien movie with these two, but this one seems pretty similar to Prometheus, then again, this is just the trailer so there might be more. I hope they answer questions brought up in the previous movie, like who the engineers are, where they're from and why they wanted to destroy the earth and other stuff, and the fact that Elizabeth and David set out on a journey to find the engineers' home planet, I hope they expand on that a bit at least.

Title: Alien: Covenant | Teaser Trailer [HD] | 20th Century FOX
Comment: Looks like a Force Awakens thing going on here. This seems to be a blend of Alien 1 and 2, with a few adjustments to make it seem different. Exploratory ship crewed by heavily armed not-quite marines, touches down on distant planet (only this time it's a fairly pleasant place - see? different!) and find a weird crashed ship containing a single egg (not hundreds this time). Despite the planet's idyllic appearance, there is some kind of strange bacterial parasite in the air which causes them to go out of their minds. Since the xenomorphs reproduce using host DNA (ie a human host results in a humanoid alien), coupled with the weird parasite, we get a completely new form of xenomorph, even badder than the 1979 original. Yay!

Title: Alien: Covenant | Teaser Trailer [HD] | 20th Century FOX
Comment:
Scott is delivering a popcorn thriller, laced with the more philosophical elements of Prometheus.  A good mix, and one that a majority audience demanded quite viciously.

People are right to guffaw at the trailer for being nothing new - it's not.  But then, what were people expecting from a Ridley Scott Alien movie?  Especially one where Scott has clearly been 'asked' to sell-out his original vision to appease said cynical, impatient audiences?

I hope the same people who whinge support fresh, new filmmaking to ensure that the universe balances out?  Or will they keep demanding total freshness from inevitably creaky franchises?

This is science-fiction and cinema: suspend your disbelief.

Title: Alien: Covenant | Teaser Trailer [HD] | 20th Century FOX
Comment:
I wonder if you guys ever get tired of your constant negative emotions. Unless there's more material out about this movie that I haven't seen that everyone in the comments has, it seems a little bit like a premature judgment don't you think?

Here we seem to have a planet full of all kinds of different forms of monster, a real exploration of the universe in the form of this, possibly mutated, planet. If you're wondering what happened to the characters in the last movie, that ship could very well be theirs, it could be all that's left.

If you were wondering what happened to the engineer home world, what if this is their home world? Or more accurately what if this is what is left after the goo was released? Either by the visitors, or by themselves thousands, if not millions of years ago?

That trailer did not seem so horrible to me, I hardly think it's worth all the hate you guys are throwing at it. The trailer may be without subtlety or Nuance, but then again, if you look at the numbers, subtlety and nuance in trailer does not sell movie tickets. Just a fact.

Title: Alien: Covenant | Teaser Trailer [HD] | 20th Century FOX
Comment:
Guys, calm down! :) 
This trailer was great, because it didn't show much of the story, like all good trailers should! All we know so far is... there will be an Alien - which is awesome! ^^ - and there will be people who have to deal with it. 
HOWEVER, the story of Prometheus (which was also great) will continue most likely. We will know more about David, what happend to Shaw, probably more about the Engineers, maybe their homeland and hopefully a bit more about their amazingly dangerous (but also very potent) substance - "the black goo". 

AND let's not forget! Ridley Scott said there will be 3 Sequels to Prometheus (which is basically "Alien 0") with the last of these sequels, Nr. 3, leading into the very first Alien movie. So it will be like: 

- Alien prequel movie 0 (known as Prometheus, introducing the alien universe: the Space Jockeys, Weyland Yutani Corp/Peter Weyland himself and his motivations, Androids, and certain incidents that "may" have lead to the creation of the "alien species") 
- Alien prequel movie 1 (>> which is Alien Covenant <<)
- Alien prequel movie 2 (>> title yet unknown <<)
- Alien prequel movie 3 (>> title yet unknown >> BUT, according to Scott THIS will be the movie that leads directly into first Alien from 1979). 

So, let's just wait and see what Alien Covenant is all about, before you all jump to conclusions AND don't forget, there will be 2 more movies coming out and fleshing out the "prequel trilogy", BUT most importantly: let's be happy and thankfull that we all will get a real "Alien Movie" made by Ridley Scott himself! :)

Title: Alien: Covenant | Teaser Trailer [HD] | 20th Century FOX
Comment:
For anyone confused on what exactly this film is about; this is a direct sequel to Prometheus/prequel to Alien. The film follows an expedition to the far reaches of the galaxy aboard the colony ship Covenant. The planet which they discover comes across as a hidden utopia until they uncover the Engineer ship and the synthetic David (who is supposedly the only survivor from Prometheus). From what we can gather David has been playing god, developing the goo further into air-borne spores and more dangerous organisms (face-huggers, xenomorphs etc.) I imagine there will be some conflict between Walter (the new synthetic also played by Michael Fassbender) and David when it comes down to their differing ideologies (synthetics typically favour the xeno's as the perfect organism - Walter may be more inclined to his crew). 
TLDR: This is a direct sequel to Prometheus, including elements of the first film - but progressing to be more familiar to the original quadrilogy in terms of what we can expect (xenomorphs).

Title: Alien: Covenant | Teaser Trailer [HD] | 20th Century FOX
Comment:
Ok, here are my thoughts on this trailer. 

The good:
+ Visually, the film will look fantastic,  without a doubt.
+ Does not show too much spoilers. Still, they shouldn't have shown the pods and the spore clips. But I am curious how the ecosystem on this planet was created and how it works.
+ Michael Fassbender will play two Androids: David and Walter.
+ I get the feeling that David will play a very antagonistic role in the film.
+ The sets look great.
+ The egg and the facehugger look very organic and not CGI.
+ The Alien is back. I am still curious what its look will be.
+ I am curious about the Neomorph, especially when it is gown up.
+ I am curious how the Engineers will appear in the film.

The bad:
- I don't quite like the music in this trailer, especially the song. The music for the Prometheus trailer was far better in my opinion.
- Apparently, the pods release spores which enter the human body through the ears. When you're on a foreign planet, wear a spacesuit with a helmet.

When I watched the trailer for the first time I had the feeling I was watching some kind of cheap horror film. Luckily they did include footage of Alien and some Prometheus elements.

Overall it is a first trailer and I am still interested how the Aliens were created.

Title: Alien: Covenant | Teaser Trailer [HD] | 20th Century FOX
Comment: In the beginning of 2015, when it was unclear whether the proposed sequel to Prometheus would be green-lit, writer/director Neill Blomkamp announced that he and actress Sigourney Weaver had been secretly working on an Alien sequel, with Ridley Scott producing. This film (working title Untitled Neill Blomkamp/Alien Project) is meant to be an alternative sequel to Aliens, which establishes a different timeline and basically ignores the events of Alien³ and Alien: Resurrection. After public approval, the film was green-lit shortly thereafter. However, at the end of 2015, it was announced that the studio had decided to develop Ridley Scott's Prometheus-sequel Alien: Covenant first. Blomkamp was asked to alter his screenplay as to not clash with Scott's story, and postpone his project indefinitely while Scott was working on Alien: Covenant and its intended sequel. Even though Blomkamp's project is still listed as under development, the film and Blomkamp's own involvement in it have become unsure. Sigourney Weaver is slated to appear in three Avatar sequels between 2018 and 2022, which could cause additional delays for the proposed Alien sequel. Blomkamp has indicated that he wants to pursue other projects in the meanwhile, and may no longer be available if it ever gets made.

Title: Alien: Covenant | Teaser Trailer [HD] | 20th Century FOX
Comment:
This looks way too futuristic...
The first too movies had this vibe of the 80's-90's in the technology placed on the ship.
Here they have these all lit up monitors, touch pads, super high quality images interfaces.
The space suits have the same Prometheus style to them...
Too much explosives... 
This looks nothing like an Alien movie. In the first two movies the characters looked far more alive - they tried to come up with solutions to the situations they got themselves into. Here, from the way it looks in the trailer, characters are dumbed down and shown to be 'scientists' but i bet that, just like in Prometheus, they will make more and more stupid decisions (like running away from a falling ship in the same direction it's falling).

Comment: Prometheus was awful, one of the most disappointing movies I've ever watched.  Great trailers don't always make great movies and Prometheus had a great one.  The only saving grace Prometheus had was it looked great in IMAX 3D but other than that, it was just awful. I couldn't care less about the engineers as most of the fans who liked Prometheus have defended it by "filling in" the gaps themselves and tried to make sense of the inane story.  This looks like the franchise is heading back to its horror roots, which I'm ok with. Scott always produces pretty films and The Martian shows that he can still create something coherent and compelling. I'll wait for the reviews on this one though before I part with my hard earned cash.

Comment: I don't know what people are bitching about, the story is continuing on from prometheus where they go looking for the planet where the engineers come from with the intention of killing them. This movie will be the first actual appearance of aliens in the storyline. It will give a whole lot more context to 'Alien' and 'Aliens' which will in turn make everybody appreciate prometheus and the other movies in the series a lot more. I don't see what this movie is doing wrong... And remember this, just because you didn't see the engineers in the trailer, doesn't mean they won't be in it or at least revolve around them. Also, why do people want the movie to connect from prometheus so quickly? As soon as they fill in the missing story line the series is over and we won't have any good Ridley Scott goodness anymore... Take your time 20th Century Fox, make 3 more if you want, just as long as there is more story to be told and Ridley is directing.

Comment:
It looks like a serious science fiction horror film.  Probably will be pretty darn good.  

But where is Dr. Elizabeth Shaw, the Engineers, and their God?  

Whatever the case is, I just hope this isn't yet another formulaic mouse trapped in a maze Alien movie which is basically what all the other Alien and/or Predator films are that take zero risks.  The fans deserve much more than a cookie cutter film.  

I hope Ridley Scott delivers the goods on this feature; in spades.  We have waited far too many decades for an Alien film which is riddled with studio executive interference.  

My sentiments also apply to the forthcoming Blade Runner sequel as well.

Title: Alien: Covenant | Teaser Trailer [HD] | 20th Century FOX
Comment:
I'm not entirely sure how I feel about this. It kind of looks like it's suffering some of the same problems of Prometheus, in which most problems are caused by crew incompetence. We're exploring an alien planet? Let's carelessly stromp all over random plantlife! It's not like we expect them to have any defense mechanisms like spores or poison or anything like that.

What's that? A weird chamber with some kind of egg thing? Let's lean in for a closer look! Only good things come from eggs, right?

Hopefully that's just me being paranoid. I don't really know much about the Alien franchise and I'm not a huge horror fan, but my best friend is and she will undoubtedly be dragging me to this movie. Hopefully it's at least good, even if I am scared out of my mind.

Title: Alien: Covenant | Teaser Trailer [HD] | 20th Century FOX
Comment:
Disappointed Noomi Rapace not in trailer or cast list at tend--she'll likely have a small part.  Wanted to follow her story. Maybe they didn't want a new Ripley to follow.  No one really jumps out in trailer but it's just a trailer.

Fassbender and even the song may hint that Scott's big focus is David, which will be interesting, but only if as a component of the alien civilization. He seems like a renegade from the Blade Runner world, maybe a bridge between these series? I'm not sure what's great about making David somehow involved in getting us to the derelict in the original--it makes the derelict in ALIEN a piece of human/Earth-related space junk instead of a completely alien object. Having space jockey be a suit over a much less-interesting humanoid alien--why was that such a great idea?

Best news is composer isn't someone who's done a lot of blockbusters; need a fresh approach.

Title: Alien: Covenant | Teaser Trailer [HD] | 20th Century FOX
Comment:
Why are the spaceships so clean/high tech looking? 

Part of the charm of Alien/Aliens was how the ships looked, instead of your usual "super clean/high tech" style they looked more like what you'd picture a worn-in spaceship of the future would look like, dirt, grime, classic style CRT monitors, lots of physical buttons like you see in jets/the space shuttle. 

It makes a lot more sense to use buttons over an electronic touch-screen, and there's a reason that even new aircraft still use older style inputs, because they are more reliable. 

What if something goes wrong with keypad? It would take the ENTIRE control of the ship away, whereas if you had individual physical buttons there would still be steps for you to recover and repair that without losing everything at once.
